"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600791","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>In view of the Pensions Ombudsman’s independent status, information about the documents he receives is held by him alone. The Pensions Ombudsman has advised that the information requested is unavailable because he does not collect data on the number of suspected fraudulent documents received by his office.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-10-17T13:36:48.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600791/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600791/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-12","Pensions: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department  holds on the number of fraudulent documents received by the Pensions Ombudsman in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","48380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600792","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>The consultation “Self-sufficient local government: 100% business rates retention” published by the Department for Communities and Local Government sought views on a range of options for devolving new responsibilities to local government including more responsibility for caring for older people. This was not a consultation on the devolution of Attendance Allowance and the Government would consult further, in good time, if any changes were to be proposed in relation to Attendance Allowance.</p><p> </p><p>The feedback from that consultation which closed on 26 September is currently being analysed and a response will be published in due course.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-17T16:38:04.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600792/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600792/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-12","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2016 to Question 43519, what assessment he has made of the potential financial effect of proposed changes to the administration of attendance allowance on local authorities with the highest proportions of attendance allowance cases in payment.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","48440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600793","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-19","<p>The Minister responsible for matters relating to the Civil Nuclear Constabulary, my noble Friend the Minister of State for Energy and Intellectual Property, is meeting with the hon. Member on 19 October, and will be meeting with the Civil Nuclear Police Federation on 3 November.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-19T10:41:38.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600793/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600793/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-12","Civil Nuclear Constabulary: Retirement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 9 September 2016 to Question 44858, if he will meet the hon. Member for Copeland and representatives of the Civil Nuclear Police Federation before Christmas 2016 to discuss the Civil Nuclear Constabulary Police Officers' retirement age.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","48438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600794","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-17","<p>Ministerial meetings with external organisations are published quarterly on the <a href="http://www.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.gov.uk</a> website at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/bis-quarterly-publications-april-to-june-2012" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/bis-quarterly-publications-april-to-june-2012</a></p><p>Information about officials is not held centrally.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-17T15:44:04.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600794/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600794/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-12","Richard Paniguian","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what meetings Ministers or officials of (a) his Department and (b) the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills had with Sir Richard Paniguian in the last 12 months; and on what dates those meeting took place.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","48387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600795","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-19","<p>Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy Ministers will be meeting with a number of energy supply companies in due course to discuss a wide range of issues. Government’s focus remains firmly on getting the best deal for consumers and ensuring the market works for everyone.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-19T12:23:28.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600795/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600795/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-12","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent discussions he has had with the CEOs of the Big Six energy companies on the availability of the cheapest energy tariff for existing customers.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","48427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600796","Department for Education","false","2016-10-27","<p>An apprenticeship is a paid job. As an apprentice, an individual can acquire skills much-valued in the labour market without having to contribute to the costs of their learning. The benefits system treats an apprentice in the same way as any other employee regardless of the sector they are working in. As an employee aged 18 or over, an apprentice may be entitled to the usual in-work benefits, such as Child Tax Credit and Working Tax Credits.</p><p>If an apprentice has children, or is aged 16 or over and does paid work of at least 16 hours a week, they could qualify for tax credits, unless they are already earning £25,000 or more per year. Further information can be found on the tax credit section of the HMRC website.</p><p>The Apprentice National Minimum Wage applies equally to all apprentices regardless of gender. Most apprentices receive more than the apprentice minimum rate of £3.40 per hour. The latest Apprenticeship Pay Survey (2014) estimates that the median hourly pay for Level 2 and Level 3 female apprentices across Great Britain is £6.36. For males it was £6.19. Differences in pay may be related to the proportion of males and females in higher and lower paid apprenticeship occupations.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-10-27T14:11:10.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600796/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600796/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600796/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-12","Apprentices: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what (a) financial and (b) childcare support is offered to young women who work as apprentices in the (i) engineering, (ii) manufacturing, (iii) hospitality, (iv) IT, (v) transport and (vi) science sectors.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","48284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600797","Department for Education","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Government has not set gender targets for the public sector when recruiting apprentices. Public sector organisations should adhere to employment and equalities legislation when recruiting apprentices.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-11-07T12:40:54.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600797/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600797/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-12","Apprentices: Gender","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she plans to encourage public sector employers to set gender targets when recruiting apprentices.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","48285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600798","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-25","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government's Open Standards Principles are helping to level the playing field for open source and proprietary software, and disaggregating government IT into smaller, more manageable components.</p><p> </p><p>The Government IT Strategy states ‘Where appropriate, government will procure open source solutions. When used in conjunction with compulsory open standards, open source presents significant opportunities for the design and delivery of interoperable solutions.’</p><p> </p><p>To support interoperability in the public sector, we have a preference for royalty-free software generated in an open and transparent manner, which is often open source.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-10-25T14:05:32.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600798/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600798/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-12","Computer Software: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the future role of open source software in industrial strategy (a) for the digital economy and (b) as an enabling platform; and what steps he is taking to support that software in relation to public sector procurement.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","48304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600799","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-19","<p>High quality broadband connectivity across the country is vital for maintaining the UK’s place at the forefront of the digital revolution and connecting people to opportunity and prosperity; in light of this, my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) has regular discussions with my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) on the important issue of broadband for everybody in an economy that works for all, and particularly those in rural locations.</p><p>In addition, the joint BEIS/DCMS Review of Business Broadband will continue to consider how consumers and businesses in rural locations can benefit from future private and public digital infrastructure initiatives.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-19T13:43:44.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600799/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600799/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-12","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent meetings he has had with Ministers of the Department for Culture, Media and Sport on rural superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","48217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600800","Department for Education","false","2016-10-27","<p>The hon. Member should have received an email response on 14 October, with a hard copy to follow.</p><p> </p><p>Skills policy is devolved, which means that the Scottish Government is responsible for managing apprenticeships in its own territory. This has been the case since the Scotland Act 1998 and UK employers understand that they need to engage with different funding bodies in different parts of the UK. The introduction of the apprenticeship levy in April 2017 will not change this position.</p><p> </p><p>On 12 August, we published detailed proposals on how we will fund apprenticeships in England when the levy is introduced in April 2017. These are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/apprenticeship-changes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/apprenticeship-changes</a>. We are committed to publishing the final apprenticeship funding policy information for England before the end of October. It will be for the Scottish Government to set out its own plans for funding apprenticeships in Scotland.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-10-27T14:13:06.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600800/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600800/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-12","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for Blaydon of 19 August 2016 on the application of the Apprenticeship Levy in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","48469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600801","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Government published in November 2014, an estimate of the projected electricity networks costs for households and small, medium and large businesses users, in Annex D of the <em>‘Estimated impacts of energy and climate change policies on energy prices and bills’.</em> These estimates reflect the eight year price control settlements that run from 2013 to 2021 (electricity transmission) and 2015 to 2023 (electricity distribution), as approved by the regulator, Ofgem.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/384404/Prices__Bills_report_2014.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/384404/Prices__Bills_report_2014.pdf</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-10-27T13:14:26.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600801/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600801/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-12","Electricity: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of proposed increases to electricity network costs on manufacturers.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","48454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600802","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-31","<p>There has been no change in the Government’s policy</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-10-31T15:34:14.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600802/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600802/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-12","Tata Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether there has been a recent change to the policy that the Government would take a 25 per cent equity stake in Tata Steel's UK assets if a sale was necessary to secure the future of UK steel.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","48453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600803","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-21","<p>Ministers and officials in the Department for International Trade are making and planning overseas visits to a wide range of markets, in order to promote the UK as a great place to do business and with which to trade. Through these discussions, we are working to ensure we take advantage of all the opportunities available to us, including through our future trading relationships. Alongside this activity, we are holding regular bilateral Ministerial dialogues on economics and trade, namely Joint Economic and Trade Committees (JETCOs), including with Indonesia, Saudi Arabia and Turkey.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-21T14:26:16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600803/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600803/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-12","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in (a) Argentina, (b) Indonesia, (c) Saudi Arabia and (d) Turkey on negotiating trade deals with the UK.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","48476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600804","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-25","<p>Ministers and officials in the Department for International Trade are working closely with counterparts across a wide range of countries and markets, in order to promote the UK as a great place to do business and with which to trade. We are taking advantage of all the opportunities available to us to ensure that Britain becomes the global leader in free trade once we leave the EU.</p><p>Most recently, the Minister for Trade Policy met his counterpart trade minister during a visit to Switzerland. My Rt. Hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade has also had a productive discussion with the Norwegian Minister for Trade, Industry and Fisheries.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-25T15:07:37.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600804/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600804/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600804/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-12","Department for International Trade: European Free Trade Association","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what recent meetings he has had with representatives from (a) Iceland, (b) Liechtenstein, (c) Norway and (d) Switzerland on trade with EFTA countries.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","48214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600805","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Birmingham, Selly Oak on 13 October, UIN 47419 and 47396.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-17T11:34:13.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600805/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600805/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-12","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many civil servants who work for his Department work in each EU member state other than the United Kingdom; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","48301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600806","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Government is currently reviewing its trade policy as the UK prepares to leave the EU. This offers us an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world: to negotiate, in time, our own trade agreements and to be a positive and powerful force for free trade. We already enjoy excellent trading relationships with our Commonwealth partners and we are committed to strengthening these further.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-17T16:42:27.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600806/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600806/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-12","Trade Agreements: Commonwealth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 10 October 2016 to Question 46317, whether he plans to review the terms of those trade deals.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","48275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600807","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Department for International Trade already has a strong and capable trade policy team which has more than doubled in size since 23 June. Over the coming months we will be developing that team to build the world class negotiating strengths needed to deliver the best outcomes for the UK. They will have the depth and breadth of expertise to handle the full range of sectoral and cross-cutting issues that arise in trade agreements, supported by analysts and lawyers.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-17T14:46:00.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600807/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600807/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600807/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-12","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many applicants his Department has received for trade negotiator positions; how many such applicants have been invited for interview; to how many such applicants job offers have been made; and how many such applicants have started work in his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","48262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600808","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-21","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Birmingham, Selly Oak on 13 October, UIN 47419 and 47396.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-21T13:08:00.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600808/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600808/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600808/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-12","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many civil servants work for his Department in EU member states excluding the United Kingdom; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","48340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600809","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-17","<p>All departments are equipping themselves with the resources they need to get the best deal for the UK. The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 250 staff plus the expertise of over 120 officials in Brussels, and we are still growing rapidly.</p><p>The term 'secondment' to refers to an interchange of staff between the Civil Service and an external organisation as such we have not brought any secondees into the Department from elsewhere in the Civil Service. All joiners from other Government departments have been on a loan basis, which refers to an interchange of staff between Civil Service departments or Agencies.<strong> </strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","48338","2016-10-17T14:15:59.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600809/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600809/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-12","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many civil servants working in his Department have been seconded from other government departments; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","48339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600810","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-17","<p>All departments are equipping themselves with the resources they need to get the best deal for the UK. The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 250 staff plus the expertise of over 120 officials in Brussels, and we are still growing rapidly.</p><p>The term 'secondment' to refers to an interchange of staff between the Civil Service and an external organisation as such we have not brought any secondees into the Department from elsewhere in the Civil Service. All joiners from other Government departments have been on a loan basis, which refers to an interchange of staff between Civil Service departments or Agencies.<strong> </strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","48339","2016-10-17T14:15:59.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600810/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600810/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-12","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many civil servants are employed by his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","48338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600811","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-08","<p>We have sought UK intellectual property practitioners’ views on the effects of the UK's withdrawal from the European Union and we are aware that this is a concern to them. We are continuing to engage with practitioners and businesses and are actively considering the options available.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-11-08T14:34:53.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600811/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600811/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-12","Trade Marks: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make it his policy to ensure that the UK intellectual property practitioners will continue to have the right to file European Trade Mark and design applications and appear on behalf of clients at the EU Intellectual Property Office after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","48358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600812","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-17","<p>There was a good reason why the Government said immediately after the referendum that it should not invoke Article 50 before the end of this year. This has given us the time to develop our negotiating strategy and avoid setting the clock ticking until our objectives are clear and agreed. As the Prime Minister has made clear, Article 50 will be triggered no later than the end of March next year.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-17T13:33:50.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600812/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600812/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-12","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, for what reasons the Government plans to activate Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union by the end of March 2017.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","48388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600813","Home Office","false","2016-10-21","<p>We wish to guarantee the rights of EU citizens already in the UK, and the only circumstances in which this would not be possible would be if British citizens’ rights in EU Member States were not protected on a reciprocal basis.</p><p>The UK is currently a member of the EU, and remains one until Article 50 negotiations have concluded. This means EU law continues to apply. Although not mandatory, after 5 years of continuous and lawful residence in the UK, EU citizens may apply for a document to confirm their EU right to reside in the UK permanently. Further information is available here: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/apply-for-a-document-certifying-permanent-residence-or-permanent-residence-card-form-eea-pr</p><p>In terms of British citizenship, under UK law, EU nationals who are married to or the civil partner of a British citizen can apply for naturalisation as a British citizen once they have obtained permanent residence in the UK.</p><p>Other EU nationals may apply for a certificate of naturalisation once they have resided in the UK for six years. This because they need to show they have completed 12 months of residence in the UK free of immigration time restrictions once they have acquired a permanent right to reside.</p><p>Further guidance on the application process to naturalise as a British citizen is available via the link below:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/application-to-naturalise-as-a-british-citizen-form-an</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-21T08:24:50.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600813/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600813/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600813/answer/previousversion/14602","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-12","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to her oral contribution of 10 October 2016, Official Report, column 62, how an EU citizen demonstrates their having lived in the UK for five or more years; how citizenship is claimed after six years; which Department will be responsible for confirming the right to (a) remain and (b) citizenship; what certification of these rights will be provided; what estimate she has made of the cost to the applicant of that process; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","48382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600814","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-17","<p>All departments are equipping themselves with the resources they need to get the best deal for the UK. The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 250 staff all based in the UK plus the expertise of over 120 officials in Brussels, and we are still growing rapidly.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-17T13:32:28.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600814/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600814/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-12","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many civil servants who work for his Department work in each EU member state other than the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","48302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600815","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear we will not give a running commentary on our EU exit negotiations. We will ensure that we engage closely with all relevant interlocutors.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-17T14:00:16.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600815/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/600815/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-12","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what recent meetings he has had with representatives from (a) Iceland, Liechtenstein, (c) Norway and (d) Switzerland on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","48225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604067","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-18","<p>Zimbabwe faces enormous political and economic challenges. A peaceful transition to a leader willing to make reforms could move Zimbabwe towards a more democratic, prosperous future. The UK does not support parties or individuals, but rather the implementation of policies that could lead to eventual normalisation of Zimbabwe’s international relations.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-18T13:46:39.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604067/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604067/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-12","Zimbabwe: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the potential implications for Zimbabwe's political and economic future in the event of the death of President Mugabe.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","906661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604257","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-18","<p>I visited Riyadh on 13 October and met with Saudi Foreign Minister Al Jubeir to discuss the airstrike on a funeral hall and efforts to revive the stalled political process in Yemen. I welcome the release of the report by the Coalition’s Joint Incidents Assessment Team into the incident. This will be used to contribute to our overall view on the approach and attitude of Saudi Arabia to international humanitarian law.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-18T13:45:05.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604257/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604257/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604257/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-12","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implications for his Department's policy on Yemen of the airstrike in Sanaa on 8 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Chris White","Warwick and Leamington","Chris White","906655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604258","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-18","<p>The Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May) has committed the Government to full engagement with the Devolved Administrations, to achieve the best possible deal for all parts of the United Kingdom, as we leave the EU.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-18T13:38:49.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604258/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604258/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604258/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-12","Brexit: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he plans to have with Ministers of the Scottish Government on the role of that Government in negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","906660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604259","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-18","<p>The UK supports the Saudi Arabian-led Coalition military intervention, which came at the request of legitimate President Hadi, to deter aggression by the Houthis, and allow for the return of the legitimate Yemeni Government.</p><p>As set out in UN Security Council (UNSC) Resolutions 2216, the UNSC continues to support President Hadi as the legitimate authority in Yemen.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-18T13:41:35.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604259/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604259/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-12","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will review the UK's support for the Saudi-led coalition forces operating in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","906654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604260","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","true","2016-10-18","<p><del class="ministerial">Although my Rt Hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Exiting the EU (Mr Davis) leads on negotiations with the EU, as I said to the Foreign Affairs Committee last week, our Departments are working closely together to get the best possible deal for the British people</del>.<ins class="ministerial">The Department for Exiting the European Union is the lead department for such matters. As the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson) said to the Foreign Affairs Committee last week, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and the Department for Exiting the European Union are working closely together to get the best possible deal for the British people.</ins></p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-18T13:18:07.357Z","2016-10-18T15:22:13.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604260/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604260/answer","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604260/answer/previousversion/14956","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-12","UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what role his Department has taken in discussions with the EU on UK membership of the single market after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","906653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598877","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-25","<p>We have recently consulted on problems faced by non-associated multi-employer schemes (NAMES) and had representations from various interested parties. We will be responding in due course.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-10-25T11:27:04.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598877/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598877/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Occupational Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to offer relief to unincorporated employers who are at risk of personal bankruptcy as a result of significant increases in defined benefit pension deficits in Non-Associated Multi-Employer Schemes following the rise in annuity costs associated with the falls in long-term interest rates in recent years; and if so, what relief will be made available.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL2185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598878","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-25","<p>The Pensions Regulator provides guidance to employers on choosing a pension scheme for their staff in order to discharge their statutory obligations under automatic enrolment. This guidance covers the choice between net pay and relief at source schemes, and the implications of net pay schemes for employees who do not pay tax.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s latest analysis of the eligibility of workers for automatic enrolment was published on 13 October 2016 in ‘Workplace Pensions: Update of analysis on Automatic Enrolment’. Information on age and earnings breakdowns for all workers can be found in table 3a on page 6, and is available in the report titled: Workplace pensions: Update of Analysis on Automatic Enrolment 2016, which is available on the gov.uk website.</p><p> </p><p>The Government does not collect data on the number of workers earning less than the personal allowance who are also members of pension schemes that operate a net pay system. The Government does not hold employee level data on employees enrolled in net pay pension schemes, as such schemes are not obliged to report pension contributions to HM Revenue and Customs. The Government does not therefore hold information on the value of tax reliefs paid out to employees in net pay schemes.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham","HL2187 ; HL2188","2016-10-25T16:51:27.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598878/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598878/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-11","Occupational Pensions: Tax Allowances","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they have taken to ensure that (1) employers, and (2) employees earning under £11,000 a year, understand the consequences of using a net pay arrangement on entitlement to tax relief.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL2186"
