"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599585","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-19","<p>The role of the Commissioner for Victims and Witnesses is defined in the Domestic Violence, Crime and Victims Act 2004. It is to promote the interests of victims and witnesses, encourage good practice in their treatment, and regularly review the operation of the Code of Practice for Victims.</p><p> </p><p>The Commissioner can make proposals to the Secretary of State for amending the Code, may report to the Secretary of State in connection with her duties, may provide advice in relation to victims or witnesses as requested, and may make recommendations to authorities which fall within her remit.</p><p> </p><p>The Commissioner has no power to investigate individual cases or make recommendations on specific complaints. In line with the process set out in the Code, a victim is entitled to make a complaint to the service provider. If they remain dissatisfied they can refer their complaint to the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman via their member of Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>We know there is more to do to further increase the rights of victims. We will announce our plans in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","47928","2016-10-19T16:46:58.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599585/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599585/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-11","Victims' Commissioner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the Victims' Commissioner has the authority to investigate complaints about breaches of the Victims' Code; and whether the Commissioner can make recommendations.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","47931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599586","Department of Health","false","2016-10-17","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-10-17T08:03:58.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599586/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599586/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-11","Prisoners: Foetal Alcohol Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the proportion of the prison population affected by (a) foetal alcohol syndrome and (b) foetal alcohol spectrum disorder.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","48196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599588","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-19","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation.</p><p> </p><p>There are currently no EU directives for which the MoJ has responsibility, and which the UK has opted into, which are awaiting transposition into UK law.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-19T14:53:30.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599588/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599588/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599588/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-11","Ministry of Justice: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which agreed EU directives have not yet been transposed directly into UK law; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","48183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599589","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-10-19","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation.</p><p> </p><p>There are no EU directives related to the Department’s responsibilities awaiting transposition into UK law.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-10-19T14:22:19.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599589/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599589/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599589/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-11","Northern Ireland Office: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, which agreed EU directives have not yet been transposed directly into UK law; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","48184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599591","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>A consultation paper on the future delivery of electoral services in Northern Ireland has now been published. The paper discusses a range of issues relating to the delivery of electoral services in Northern Ireland, including the provision of local services following the introduction of digital registration. I look forward to receiving the views of all those with an interest in this important issue.</p><p> </p><p>The consultation paper is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications</a>.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-10-17T14:22:21.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599591/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599591/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599591/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-11","Electoral Register: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps he plans to take to retain the network of electoral offices in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","48008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599593","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-10-18","<p>The open border between the UK and the Republic of Ireland existed for many years before either country was a member of the European Union and it has served both countries well. There is a strong will – within this Government, among the Northern Ireland parties and in the Irish Government – to preserve the open border. We must now work closely together to ensure that as the UK leaves the EU we find shared solutions to the challenges and maximise the opportunities.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-10-18T11:44:40.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599593/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599593/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599593/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599593/answer/previousversion/14744","Biography information for James Brokenshire","21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-11","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the Government's policy is on the nature of the border controls between the UK and the Republic of Ireland after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","48042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599594","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-17","<p>We are considering in detail the advantages and disadvantages of several different approaches. But we will not undermine the Government’s negotiating position by giving a running commentary on our position before negotiations have even started.</p><p>The Prime Minister has spoken of getting a bespoke deal for the country - what we want is the right deal, on both trade for the UK and our relationship with the EU<strong>.</strong></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-10-17T15:56:03.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599594/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599594/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-11","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether he plans for any trade agreement between the UK and EU to come into force after the UK leaves the EU to be undertaken alongside negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","48043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599595","Prime Minister","false","2016-10-19","<p>I meet members of the public all the time.</p><p> </p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2016-10-19T08:08:08.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599595/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599595/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599595/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-10-11","Prime Minister: Domestic Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, on what occasions she has met and conversed with members of the public in her official capacity since she became Prime Minister on 13 July 2016.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","47985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599597","Scotland Office","false","2016-10-18","<p>Households in Scotland with dynamically teleswitched meters can switch to a single-rate or an Economy 7 tariff offered by their existing supplier or by a rival supplier. At present, some suppliers may require the dynamically teleswitched meter to be replaced at a cost to the customer and they may suffer a loss of functionality. In its final report in June, the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) included in its remedies an order on energy suppliers with more than 50,000 domestic customers to make all their single-rate electricity tariffs available to all existing and new domestic electricity customers with restricted meters, without requiring the meter to be replaced. Suppliers will also need to ensure these customers receive regular information on the options to switch supplier or tariff. The Citizens Advice will become a recognised provider of information and support for customers with restricted meters.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","47989","2016-10-18T11:12:31.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599597/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599597/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599597/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-11","Electricity: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what opportunities are available to households in Scotland with dynamically teleswitched meters to switch between electricity suppliers.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","47988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599599","Scotland Office","false","2016-10-18","<p>Households in Scotland with dynamically teleswitched meters can switch to a single-rate or an Economy 7 tariff offered by their existing supplier or by a rival supplier. At present, some suppliers may require the dynamically teleswitched meter to be replaced at a cost to the customer and they may suffer a loss of functionality. In its final report in June, the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) included in its remedies an order on energy suppliers with more than 50,000 domestic customers to make all their single-rate electricity tariffs available to all existing and new domestic electricity customers with restricted meters, without requiring the meter to be replaced. Suppliers will also need to ensure these customers receive regular information on the options to switch supplier or tariff. The Citizens Advice will become a recognised provider of information and support for customers with restricted meters.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","47988","2016-10-18T11:12:31.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599599/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599599/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599599/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-11","Electricity: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what tariffs are available to households in Scotland with dynamically teleswitched meters that may want to switch between electricity suppliers.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","47989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599600","Scotland Office","false","2016-10-18","<p>We do not hold information on how many households in Scotland and the Highland area of Scotland have their electricity supplies controlled by dynamically teleswitched meters. In Ofgem’s response to the Competition Markets Authority’s Notice of Remedies published in August 2015, it was estimated that there were 160,000 households across Great Britain with dynamically teleswitched meters in operation at the end of 2014.</p><p> </p><p>The Competition Markets Authority’s Notice of Remedies is available online at:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/561e1fbaed915d39bc000013/Ofgem__revised_with_additional_material_.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/561e1fbaed915d39bc000013/Ofgem__revised_with_additional_material_.pdf</a>.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-10-18T11:10:27.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599600/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599600/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599600/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-11","Electricity: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many households in (a) Scotland and (b) the Highland area of Scotland have their electricity supplies controlled by dynamically teleswitched meters.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","48013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599601","Scotland Office","false","2016-10-18","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation.</p><p> </p><p>The Scotland Office has no EU Directives awaiting transposition into UK law.</p><p><strong><br> <br> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-10-18T11:07:28.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599601/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599601/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599601/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-11","Scotland Office: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, which agreed EU directives have not yet been transposed directly into UK law; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","48185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599603","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-19","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation.</p><p> </p><p>There are currently 23 EU Directives relating to my Department’s responsibilities awaiting transposition into UK law.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-19T09:44:48.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599603/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599603/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599603/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-11","Department for Transport: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which agreed EU directives have not yet been transposed directly into UK law; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","48186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599604","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>It is important that we do ensure good documentation of major projects across government to learn from the past and ensure knowledge is shared easily. I will consider in due course what is the right way to do this but the advertised recruitment is not going ahead.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","48053 ; 48208 ; 48209","2016-10-17T10:48:02.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599604/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599604/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the total budget is of the team of writers being hired by his Department to help write the story of High Speed 2 from inception to present day.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","48052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599605","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>It is important that we do ensure good documentation of major projects across government to learn from the past and ensure knowledge is shared easily. I will consider in due course what is the right way to do this but the advertised recruitment is not going ahead.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","48052 ; 48208 ; 48209","2016-10-17T10:48:02.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599605/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599605/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to ensure that his Department's officials being recruited to help write the story of High Speed 2 from inception to the present day meet with all hon. Members representing parliamentary constituencies along the route.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","48053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599606","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-18","<p>The Secretary of State has not discussed this issue with the Chancellor of the Exchequer. A final decision on whether to fund further discounts to users of the bridges has yet to be taken.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-18T09:02:37.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599606/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599606/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-11","River Mersey: Bridges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the introduction of tolls on the Mersey Gateway and Silver Jubilee bridges; and whether a decision has been taken on discounts for use of those bridges for local businesses and residents.","false","Biography information for Sir George Howarth","Knowsley","Mr George Howarth","48119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599608","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-18","<p>The Secretary of State for Transport has not produced an assessment of the effect of tolls on the Mersey Gateway and Silver Jubilee bridges on the (a) finances, (b) employment levels, (c) employment choices and (d) road travel habits of residents of Knowsley. The Mersey Gateway Bridge scheme is being promoted by Halton Borough Council and it is for them to justify the costs for users of the new bridge. A range of discounts will be available for frequent users of the crossing.</p><p> </p><p>In approving the scheme the Government considered the case for change, the economic case, and that the scheme is viable, affordable and achievable. In line with other estuarial crossings, and as there will be improved travel across the Mersey, users are expected to part fund the infrastructure.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-18T08:40:09.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599608/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599608/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-11","River Mersey: Bridges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of tolls on the Mersey Gateway and Silver Jubilee bridges on the (a) finances, (b) employment levels, (c) employment choices and (d) road travel habits of residents of Knowsley.","false","Biography information for Sir George Howarth","Knowsley","Mr George Howarth","48118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599609","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Government is currently considering all the recommendations in the Law Commission’s report on taxi and private hire regulation in England and Wales and will formally respond to the Law Commission and announce its intentions once this scrutiny is completed.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has no current plans to amend legislation in respect of cross-border working. The Deregulation Act 2015 enables licensed operators in England and Wales to subcontract bookings to licensed operators in another district, any private hire vehicle operator in London or an operator in Scotland. This power was already possible in London through The Private Hire Vehicles (London) Act 1998. This was a recommendation from the Law Commission’s review of taxi and private hire services.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-17T09:21:29.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599609/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599609/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-11","Taxis: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the Government plans to respond to the recommendations of the Law Commission Report on taxi and private hire vehicle licensing, published in May 2014; and whether it plans to take steps to permit more local authority cross-border use of such vehicles.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","48029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599610","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>The government’s recent consultation on bringing in tougher sanctions received near unanimous support for tougher penalties. The Secretary of State for Transport has pledged to bring tougher sanctions in as soon as possible, we expect them to take effect in the first half of 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Anyone using a hand-held device while driving will face higher on the spot fines and more points on their driving licence than they do today.</p><p> </p><p>The government is also developing a hard-hitting THINK! campaign to tackle this issue, to make it socially unacceptable like drink driving or not wearing a seatbelt.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-17T09:26:25.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599610/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599610/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-11","Road Traffic Offences: Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the number of people using mobile phones while driving; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","48039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599611","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-18","<p>It is for local authorities and police to decide how they wish to operate speed cameras. The Department issued guidance in 2007 entitled “Use of speed and red-light cameras for traffic enforcement: guidance on deployment, visibility and signing”. I wrote to all local authorities in England and Wales on 20 October 2015 to remind them of the guidance which is available on gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p>Some cameras have the capability to photograph vehicles from the front and rear, whereas others do not. Where front and back photographing is possible, it will be for highway authorities and the Police to decide whether such cameras are most suitable.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-18T13:10:41.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599611/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599611/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-11","Speed Limits: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for what reasons his Department deploys speed cameras that photograph vehicles from the (a) front and (b) rear on (i) trunk roads and (ii) motorways; and for what reasons his Department does not have a consistent policy on the deployment and use of such speed cameras.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","47984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599613","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>It is important that we do ensure good documentation of major projects across government to learn from the past and ensure knowledge is shared easily. I will consider in due course what is the right way to do this but the advertised recruitment is not going ahead.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","48052 ; 48053 ; 48209","2016-10-17T10:48:02.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599613/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599613/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the job vacancy notice DFT/649/16/DFTC, published by his Department in October 2016, how his Department expects the report and slide pack which form part of the project to write the story of High Speed 2 from inception to the present day to be used; and who his Department expects to use that report and slide pack.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","48208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599614","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-17","<p>It is important that we do ensure good documentation of major projects across government to learn from the past and ensure knowledge is shared easily. I will consider in due course what is the right way to do this but the advertised recruitment is not going ahead.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","48052 ; 48053 ; 48208","2016-10-17T10:48:02.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599614/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599614/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the job vacancy notice DFT/649/16/DFTC, published by his Department in October 2016, who will be responsible for editing the report and slide pack which form part of the project to write the story of High Speed 2 from inception to the present day.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","48209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599615","Wales Office","false","2016-10-18","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation.</p><p> </p><p>There are no EU directives within the Wales Office’s responsibilities.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-10-18T11:53:48.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599615/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599615/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-10-11","Wales Office: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, which agreed EU directives have not yet been transposed directly into UK law; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","48188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599616","Women and Equalities","false","2016-10-21","<p>We have more women on boards than ever before, and no all-male boards in the FTSE 100. I fully endorse the business-led target of 33% women on FTSE 350 boards by 2020. To achieve this, we have established the new, independent Hampton-Alexander Review that will have a particular focus on improving gender representation in the all-important executive layer of FTSE companies.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-10-21T13:13:36.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599616/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599616/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-10-11","Females: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps she is taking to improve the representation of women at senior executive levels in (a) FTSE 100 and (b) all businesses.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","48133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599618","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-18","<p>Pregnancy and maternity-related discrimination in the workplace is both unlawful and unacceptable, and has no place in today’s society. That is why the former Department for Business, Innovation and Skills and the Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) jointly commissioned independent research to better understand the issues so that appropriate steps can be taken to address the situation.</p><p>The Government is committed to tackling pregnancy and maternity discrimination and we are taking action as promised in our response on 22 March 2016 to recommendations made by the EHRC. We are working with a range of partners including EHRC and Acas to promote opportunities for women, including pregnant women and new mothers; to ensure that female talent is recognised and rewarded; and to make more employers aware of their legal obligations.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-18T13:41:10.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599618/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599618/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Pregnancy: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to address levels of discrimination in the work-place for women who are pregnant.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","48150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599619","Department for Education","false","2016-11-10","<p>The Government does not hold information on the number of employers that publish targets for the ratio of male to female apprentices.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-11-10T15:41:10.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599619/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599619/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-11","Apprentices: Gender","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will estimate the number of employers which publish targets for the ratio of male to female apprentices.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","48128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599620","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-17","<p>We do not believe there is an inherent or structural reason why female representation in the House of Commons should be affected by updating Parliamentary boundaries. Each constituent part of the United Kingdom will be treated equally. The appointment of candidates to contest these new seats will be a matter for political parties. We consider that it is primarily for political parties to ensure more diverse representation (including that of women) in the House of Commons through their selection of candidates.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-17T09:43:57.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599620/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599620/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-11","Members: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the effect of proposed boundary changes on the potential number of female hon. Members in the next Parliament.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","48001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599621","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Prime Minister is clear that tackling poverty and disadvantage, and delivering real social reform, is a priority for this Government and we will be coming back to the House with a number of announcements over the coming months.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-10-17T15:05:32.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599621/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599621/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Social Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when his Department plans to publish its Life Changes Strategy.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","47998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599623","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>The consultation “Self-sufficient local government: 100% business rates retention” published by the Department for Communities and Local Government sought views on a range of options for devolving new responsibilities to local government including more responsibility for caring for older people.</p><p> </p><p>The feedback from that consultation which closed on 26 September is currently being analysed and a response will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Government would undertake a further consultation, accompanied by a relevant impact assessment, if any changes were to be proposed in relation to Attendance Allowance.</p><p> </p><p>The information on administrative costs related to Attendance Allowance is collected by DWP but is not currently available for the financial year 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested on applications is not available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Information on claims awarded under the special rules for people with terminal illness is available from the DWP Tabulation Tool: <a href="http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/tabtool.html" target="_blank">http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/tabtool.html</a>.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","48092 ; 48103","2016-10-17T16:28:49.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599623/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599623/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 8 September 2016 to Question 44901, if he will make the advertising costs of attendance allowance readily available either (a) during or (b) after the consultation on the devolution of attendance allowance.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","48010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599624","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-19","<p>The role of contracted Assessment Providers is to carry out health and disability assessments on behalf of the Department. They do not determine if a claim to Personal Independence Payment (PIP) is successful. They provide a report to DWP decision makers who then determine entitlement to benefit. No targets are in place as to how many applications are successful.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","47986","2016-10-19T16:20:09.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599624/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599624/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department's staff performance monitoring includes key performance indicators on how many personal independence payment (PIP) claims are (a) accepted and (b) rejected by those staff who are PIP assessors.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","47987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599625","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-19","<p>The role of contracted Assessment Providers is to carry out health and disability assessments on behalf of the Department. They do not determine if a claim to Personal Independence Payment (PIP) is successful. They provide a report to DWP decision makers who then determine entitlement to benefit. No targets are in place as to how many applications are successful.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","47987","2016-10-19T16:20:09.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599625/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599625/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether personal independence payment (PIP) assessors employed by (a) his Department, (b) Capita and (c) Atos Healthcare have targets of how many PIP claims they (i) reject and (ii) accept.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","47986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599626","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-19","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply I gave to his previous questions numbered 47755 and 47757 (PQs asked on Tuesday 11<sup>th</sup> October 2016).</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-19T11:31:11.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599626/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599626/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what qualifications are required of people who work as personal independence payment assessors.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","48021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599627","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-19","<p>There are special rules and procedures for people who are terminally ill and make a claim to Personal Independence Payment (PIP) meaning that their claims are fast tracked and they are guaranteed immediate, unconditional entitlement to the enhanced rate of the daily living component, without an assessment of their needs.</p><p>To ensure correct decisions are made as quickly as possible, factual information on the claimant’s condition, clinical features and current/planned treatment is captured on the DS1500 form. This is completed by their GP, hospital consultant or delegated practice/special nurse (e.g. a Macmillan nurse).</p><p>The Department has worked closely with organisations supporting terminally ill people, such as Macmillan Cancer Support, to ensure that the service we offer works as effectively and efficiently as possible. This collaborative approach has resulted in the Department introducing a dedicated telephone service for terminally ill claimants and introducing an electronic method of submitting a DS1500 form from the claimant’s medical practitioner.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-19T11:18:29.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599627/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599627/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Personal Independence Payment: Terminal Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what measures his Department has put in place to ensure that terminally ill patients' needs are fully considered during personal independence payment assessments.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","47939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599629","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>Employment and Support Allowance can be paid at the assessment phase rate pending the appeal hearing as long as the conditions of entitlement are satisfied. Employment and Support Allowance is not payable pending an appeal where a claimant has previously been found fit for work following a Work Capability Assessment and makes a repeat claim for benefit and is found to be fit for work again.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-17T16:32:40.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599629/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599629/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Employment and Support Allowance: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, in a case where an applicant has been refused employment and support allowance (ESA), the disallowance has been confirmed following mandatory reconsideration and an appeal against the refusal has been submitted, in what circumstances ESA is payable pending the outcome of the appeal.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","47978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599630","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-19","<p>The Department does not prescribe providers with criteria on how they should pay salary or bonuses to their staff. That is purely a commercial decision for the assessment provider.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-19T11:11:05.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599630/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599630/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria determine whether personal independence payment assessors receive financial bonuses in addition to their salary.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","47959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599632","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>The consultation “Self-sufficient local government: 100% business rates retention” published by the Department for Communities and Local Government sought views on a range of options for devolving new responsibilities to local government including more responsibility for caring for older people.</p><p> </p><p>The feedback from that consultation which closed on 26 September is currently being analysed and a response will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Government would undertake a further consultation, accompanied by a relevant impact assessment, if any changes were to be proposed in relation to Attendance Allowance.</p><p> </p><p>The information on administrative costs related to Attendance Allowance is collected by DWP but is not currently available for the financial year 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested on applications is not available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Information on claims awarded under the special rules for people with terminal illness is available from the DWP Tabulation Tool: <a href="http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/tabtool.html" target="_blank">http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/tabtool.html</a>.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","48010 ; 48092","2016-10-17T16:28:49.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599632/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599632/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 8 September 2016 to Question 44898, if he will make it his policy to collect the total administrative costs related to attendance allowance in 2015-16 (a) during the consultation and (b) after the consultation on the devolution of attendance allowance.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","48103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599633","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-18","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-18T14:44:04.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599633/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599633/answer","PQ48154 v.03 (1) (1).pdf","PQ48154 v.03 (1) (1).pdf","UKSA response to 48154 ","UKSA response to 48154 ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599633/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-11","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate his Department has made of the net change in the number of jobs in the UK since 23 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","48154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599634","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-19","<p>Our country remains open for business. Employment is at a record high with a almost a million new businesses in our country since 2010 and we will always welcome those with the skills, the drive and the expertise to make our nation better still. The Prime Minister has been clear that she wants to protect the status of EU nationals already living here, and the only circumstances in which that wouldn’t be possible is if British citizens’ rights in European member states were not protected.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-10-19T16:39:15.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599634/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599634/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599634/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Employment: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to safeguard the jobs of EU nationals living in the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","48139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599636","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-19","<p>Our primary goal is to help care leavers get into work wherever possible and our interventions are tailored to achieve this. Care leavers aged between 18 and 21 have the opportunity to join the Work Programme from day one of their benefit claim, so that they receive tailored, locally-appropriate employment support at the earliest opportunity. We also provide additional support, over and above the standard Jobcentre Plus offer, to young claimants, including care leavers, aged 18-24. Work Coaches tailor interventions to the needs of the individual to address a variety of barriers to work, including improving job search skills, referral to skills and other work-related training such as Traineeships, Apprenticeships and work experience.</p><p>We have safeguards in place for care leavers along with other claimants who may be considered vulnerable. Work Coaches support all claimants with complex needs, or who require additional support, to ensure that they fully understand what they have been asked to do to enable them to access DWP benefits and use our services.</p><p>Care leavers, like all claimants, take ownership of planning how they will meet their requirements and ultimately secure employment. They will be supported by their Work Coach who will assist them in meeting their requirements through providing encouragement and direction, using a range of communication methods.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-10-19T16:28:47.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599636/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599636/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Social Security Benefits: Care Leavers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the report by the Children's Society, The cost of being care free, published in June 2016, if he will take steps to provide additional protection for care leavers to reduce the number of benefits sanctions being applied to such people.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","48112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599637","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>The consultation “Self-sufficient local government: 100% business rates retention” published by the Department for Communities and Local Government sought views on a range of options for devolving new responsibilities to local government including more responsibility for caring for older people.</p><p> </p><p>The feedback from that consultation which closed on 26 September is currently being analysed and a response will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Government would undertake a further consultation, accompanied by a relevant impact assessment, if any changes were to be proposed in relation to Attendance Allowance.</p><p> </p><p>The information on administrative costs related to Attendance Allowance is collected by DWP but is not currently available for the financial year 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested on applications is not available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Information on claims awarded under the special rules for people with terminal illness is available from the DWP Tabulation Tool: <a href="http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/tabtool.html" target="_blank">http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/tabtool.html</a>.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","48010 ; 48103","2016-10-17T16:28:49.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599637/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599637/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Attendance Allowance: Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 8 September 2016 to Question 44900, if he will publish the number of people with cancer who applied for attendance allowance under the special rules for people with terminal illness in each of the last five years either (a) during or (b) after the consultation on the devolution of attendance allowance.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","48092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599638","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-18","<p>Shared Parental Leave and Pay came into effect in December 2014 for the parents of children due or placed for adoption from 5 April 2015. The Coalition Government ran a multi-channel campaign comprising of PR, digital and advertising activity aimed at parents and their employers leading up to the scheme coming into effect. The scheme received national press coverage at the time of introduction and subsequently, and was also promoted through a number of stakeholder focussed events, targeted at parents, employers and HR professionals.</p><p>Information and advice on shared parental leave is available on GOV.UK and through Acas.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-18T13:42:39.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599638/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599638/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599638/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Parental Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to promote and enable partners to share parental leave.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","48131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599639","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-18","<p>In 2011, the Coalition Government consulted on a number of options to modernise employment entitlements relating to families. This led to the introduction of Shared Parental Leave and Pay for working parents; and the provisions in the Children and Families Act 2014 which enable Ministers to make Regulations to extend paternity leave and increase the rate of pay.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-18T13:41:52.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599639/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599639/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what research his Department has recently undertaken into the potential benefits of increasing paternity leave for men.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","48132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599640","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-19","<p>The only agreed EU directive which has not yet been transposed directly into UK law is <em>2013/59/Euratom (laying down basic safety standards for protection against the dangers arising from exposure to ionising radiation, and repealing Directives 89/618/Euratom, 90/641/Euratom, 96/29/Euratom, 97/43/Euratom and 2003/122/Euratom). </em></p><p>This is a joint transposition with the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy. The transposition deadline is 6 February 2018.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-10-19T15:47:17.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599640/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599640/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Department for Work and Pensions: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which agreed EU directives have not yet been transposed directly into UK law; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","48189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599642","Department for Education","false","2016-10-18","<p>The Apprentice National Minimum Wage (NMW) applies equally to all apprentices regardless of gender (for the first year, if aged 19, the appropriate NMW for age applies). From October 2016, this rate increased to £3.40 per hour.</p><p> </p><p>Most apprentices receive more than the minimum wage; the latest Apprenticeship Pay Survey (2014) estimates that the median hourly pay for Level 2 and Level 3 apprentices across Great Britain is £6.31. For males it was £6.19 and for females it was £6.36. Differences in pay may occur due to the proportion of males and females in higher or lower paid apprenticeships.</p><p> </p><p>The Government places importance on compliance with minimum wage legislation and the effective enforcement of it. Everyone who is entitled to the minimum wage should receive it.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-10-18T15:33:43.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599642/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599642/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-11","Apprentices: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to prevent wage discrepancies between male and female apprentices.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","48130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599643","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-18","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation.</p><p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy is responsible for transposition of the following agreed Directives: 2013/30/EU, 2013/55/EU, 2013/53/EU, 2014/33/EU, 2014/34/EU, 2014/29/EU, 2014/30/EU, 2014/35/EU, 2014/31/EU, 2014/32/EU, 2015/13/EU, 2014/53/EU, 2014/68/EU, 2014/95/EU, 2014/104/EU, 2015/2302/EU, 2015/2436/EU, 2014/87/EU, 2013/59/EU.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-18T13:10:56.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599643/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599643/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599643/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which agreed EU directives have not yet been transposed directly into UK law; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","48169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599644","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-19","<p>The Government does not regulate the sale of decommissioned emergency fire and rescue vehicles. It is for each emergency rescue authority to dispose appropriately of its assets as it sees fit.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-19T15:56:53.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599644/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599644/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599644/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Emergency Services: Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will regulate the sale of ex-emergency service vehicles.","false","Biography information for Gerald Jones","Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney","Gerald Jones","48100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599645","Department for Education","false","2016-10-24","<p>Apprentices are employed from day one. They acquire skills much valued in the labour market without having to contribute to the costs of their learning. The benefits system treats an apprentice in the same way as any other employee.</p><p> </p><p>As an employee aged 18 or over, an apprentice may be entitled to the usual in-work benefits, such as Child Tax Credit and Working Tax Credits.</p><p> </p><p>If an apprentice has children, or is aged 16 or over and does paid work of at least 16 hours a week, they could qualify for tax credits, unless they are already earning £25,000 or more per year. Further information can be found on the tax credit section of the HMRC website. Universal Credit will make it easier and less worrying for claimants to try out a job or work more hours because their benefits will not automatically stop if they do so.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-10-24T09:34:30.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599645/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599645/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599645/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-11","Apprentices: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what support is on offer to apprentices who need help covering childcare costs and if she will take steps to extend such support to match that available to other workers.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","48129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599646","Department for Education","false","2016-10-18","<p>We want to increase the quality and quantity of all apprenticeships, including for those from a black, Asian, and minority ethnic (BAME) background.</p><p>We have publically committed to increasing the number of BAME apprentices by 20% to 11.9% overall by 2020, from just under 10% in the last parliament. Targeted campaigns and a network of 18 employer diversity champions are driving progress. In 2014/15, 10.6% of those starting an apprenticeship were from a BAME background.</p><p>We have taken action through our marketing campaign ‘Get in Go Far’ to ensure that there is clear representation from BAME apprentices. Research undertaken prior to the campaign ensured that it could reach a diverse audience. The employer diversity champions are committed to sharing good practice and raising awareness of apprenticeships amongst employers.</p><p>Research has been commissioned to explore potential barriers that BAME applicants for apprenticeships face so that we can provide support to improve the success rates of this group. We have started detailed analysis of apprenticeship data to identify areas of under-representation and areas of potential for growth. We are currently developing options to take forward.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-10-18T15:32:50.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599646/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599646/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599646/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-11","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to  increase diversity in apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","48127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599648","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-18","<p>In the period 1<sup>st</sup> April 2014 to 31<sup>st</sup> March 2016 HMRC identified National Minimum Wage arrears totalling £981,514 as a result of investigations into social care employers.</p><p>The National Living Wage was introduced from April 2016. Data for 2016/17 is not yet available.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-18T13:12:56.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599648/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599648/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Social Services: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much has been paid to social care workers by employers since HM Revenue and Customs introduced the self-correction process for recovering arrears for workers paid below the (a) national minimum wage and (b) national living wage.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","47961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599650","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-18","<p>Where HM Revenue and Customs instructs employers to self-correct, the employer must declare details of the arrears subsequently paid to workers. HMRC perform checks before accepting that pay has been corrected.</p><p>HMRC take the circumstances of individual employers into account when instructing to self-correct. If the value of the arrears repaid does not reflect what HMRC expect based on the facts of the case, they can open an investigation to ensure that workers receive what they are owed. Where employers need assistance determining the value of the arrears owed, HMRC will work with them to ensure they get it right.</p><p>HMRC’s assurance process involves performing a sample check that arrears have been paid correctly. Workers are selected and contacted by telephone and correspondence to confirm that they have received the arrears they are owed, in the amount that the employer has reported.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-18T13:12:15.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599650/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599650/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what verification process is used by HM Revenue and Customs to ensure that the level of arrears paid to workers using the self-correction process by employers found to be non-compliant with the (a) national minimum wage and (b) national living wage is a true reflection of the amount the workforce is owed.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","47962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599652","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-18","<p>Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy Ministers will be meeting energy supply companies in due course to discuss a range of issues.</p><p>Under the terms of the supply licence, suppliers are required to offer customers a wide choice of payment methods, and this must include payment by cash and payment in advance through a prepayment meter.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-18T16:54:07.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599652/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599652/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599652/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with energy suppliers on tariffs for customers who do not elect to pay for services online.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","47965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599653","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-25","<p>The UK played an important role in securing the global climate Agreement reached in Paris in December 2015. The UK has started its domestic process to enable ratification of the Paris Agreement and will complete this before the end of the year.</p><p>The UK also played a key role in securing a major global climate deal to combat aviation emissions, reached at the 39th Assembly of the International Civil Aviation Organization on 6 October 2016.</p><p>We will provide at least £5.8bn from the UK aid budget between 2016 and 2020 as climate finance which will continue to support developing countries to mitigate and adapt to climate change. This should help promote green investment required to meet the well below 2 degree goal set in Paris.</p><p>Domestically we are delivering against the Paris climate deal through our UK Climate Change Act which commits us to reduce emissions by at least 80% by 2050. One of the first acts of this Government was to pass the fifth carbon budget into law – it is equivalent to a 57% reduction on 1990 levels by 2030.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-10-25T14:02:13.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599653/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599653/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599653/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to tackle global climate change.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","47955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599654","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-19","<p>Most of the UK’s existing coal fired power stations are old, relatively inefficient and require investment to reduce the level of damaging pollutants they emit. We expect to consult shortly on the closure of unabated coal stations.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-19T11:21:45.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599654/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599654/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599654/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Coal Fired Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when his Department plans to publish the consultation on the Government's commitment to phase out coal-fired power stations.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","47945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599655","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-19","<p>Data on the number of smart electricity and gas meters installed in Great Britain is set out in the Government’s ‘Smart Meters, Quarterly Report to end June 2016’, published on 29 September 2016:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-release-and-data-smart-meters-great-britain-quarter-2-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-release-and-data-smart-meters-great-britain-quarter-2-2016</a></p><p>Across Great Britain, more than 4.2 million meters are now operating under the Programme. Northern Ireland is undertaking a separate roll-out programme.</p><p>Data is not collected from energy suppliers in a format that allows constituency or London-borough level data to be produced.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-19T10:40:29.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599655/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599655/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599655/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate his Department has made of the number of households in (a) Feltham and Heston constituency, (b) all London boroughs and (c) the UK that are equipped with intelligent smart metering systems.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","48016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599657","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-18","<p>HM Revenue and Customs does not have a formal process for revisiting previously non-compliant employers.</p><p>However, HMRC responds to 100% of worker complaints, including into employers where arrears have previously been found. As well as responding to complaints, HMRC also maintains a risk-led targeted enforcement programme which involves proactively investigating employers in high-risk sectors.</p><p>HMRC will always take action where they believe an employer is not paying the National Minimum Wage/National Living Wage to ensure that every worker receives what they are legally entitled to.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-18T13:11:32.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599657/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599657/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599657/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 29 September 2016 to Question 44820, whether any subsequent action is taken by HM Revenue and Customs against employers named and shamed for non-compliance with the national minimum wage and national living wage to check that they have changed their business practice and are continuing to pay their workforce legally.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","47967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599658","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-19","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy does not hold estimates on the number of households in the Highland area of Scotland with dynamically teleswitched meters who receive their electricity supply under Scottish Power’s Comfort Control tariff.</p><p>In Ofgem’s response to CMA Notice of Remedies published in August 2015, it was estimated that there were 160,000 households across Great Britain with dynamically teleswitched meters in operation at the end of 2014:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/561e1fbaed915d39bc000013/Ofgem__revised_with_additional_material_.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/561e1fbaed915d39bc000013/Ofgem__revised_with_additional_material_.pdf</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-19T10:40:52.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599658/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599658/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599658/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Electricity: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many households in the Highland area of Scotland with dynamically teleswitched meters receive their electricity supply from Scottish Power.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","47990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599659","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-19","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy does not hold estimates on the number of households in the Highland area of Scotland with dynamically teleswitched meters who receive their electricity supply under Scottish Power’s Comfort Control tariff.</p><p>In Ofgem’s response to CMA Notice of Remedies published in August 2015, it was estimated that there were 160,000 households across Great Britain with dynamically teleswitched meters in operation at the end of 2014:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/561e1fbaed915d39bc000013/Ofgem__revised_with_additional_material_.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/561e1fbaed915d39bc000013/Ofgem__revised_with_additional_material_.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-19T10:40:04.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599659/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599659/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599659/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Electricity: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many households in the Highland area of Scotland with dynamically teleswitched meters receive their electricity supply under Scottish Power's Comfort Control tariff.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","47991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599660","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-19","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy does not hold estimates on the number of households in the UK who have their electricity supplies controlled by dynamically teleswitched meters.</p><p>In Ofgem’s response to CMA Notice of Remedies published in August 2015, it was estimated that there were 160,000 households across Great Britain with dynamically teleswitched meters in operation at the end of 2014:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/561e1fbaed915d39bc000013/Ofgem__revised_with_additional_material_.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/561e1fbaed915d39bc000013/Ofgem__revised_with_additional_material_.pdf</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-19T10:41:54.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599660/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599660/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599660/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Electricity: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many households in the UK have their electricity supplies controlled by dynamically teleswitched meters.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","48014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599661","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-20","<p>The Government is committed to maintain and enhance the strength of our research base. This is why we have protected the science resource budget in real terms from its 2015/16 level of £4.7 billion for the rest of the parliament, as well as committing to invest in new scientific infrastructure on a record scale – £6.9 billion over the period 2015-2021, including £150 million for the Dementia Research Institute.</p><p> </p><p>The Treasury decision to underwrite the grants of competitively bid for EU research funding will give British participants and their EU partners the assurance and certainty needed to plan ahead for projects that can run over many years. We are committed to ensure that the UK continues to be a world leader in international science, including research on dementia.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-10-20T11:35:24.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599661/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599661/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599661/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-11","Dementia: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on funding for dementia research.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","47999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599663","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-17","<p>On 1<sup>st</sup> August 2016, my Rt hon. Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade held meetings in Belfast with Northern Ireland Executive First Minister Arlene Foster MLA and Minister for the Economy Simon Hamilton MLA. A range of topics were discussed including growing exports for Northern Ireland and establishing new UK trading relationships around the globe. During these constructive discussions he underlined the importance that he places on the Department for International Trade serving the whole of the United Kingdom.</p><p>The Department for International Trade continues to engage with Republic of Ireland officials, collaborating on trade and exports including most recently at the meeting of UK Permanent Secretaries with their Republic of Ireland Counterparts in London on 7 October.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-17T11:32:25.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599663/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599663/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-11","Trade: Northern Ireland and Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts and officials in the Irish government and the Northern Ireland Executive on trade and export opportunities in (a) Northern Europe, (b) the US and (c) Asia Pacific countries.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","48007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599664","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-19","<p><strong>The Department for International Trade and other departments, have extensive contact with their counterparts in Pakistan. Discussions routinely cover enhancing bilateral trade and investment, and business climate reform in Pakistan. The Prime Minister met Pakistan’s Prime Minister Sharif on 20 September, and they discussed trade relations.</strong></p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-19T16:44:56.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599664/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599664/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-11","Overseas Trade: Pakistan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he has had with (a) the government of Pakistan and (b) other key stakeholders on promoting UK trade with that country.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","48020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599665","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Westmorland and Lonsdale on 10 October, UIN 46309.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-17T11:30:27.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599665/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599665/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-11","Department for International Trade: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 10 October 2016 to Question 46319, what overseas visits he has made as Secretary of State for International Trade since the establishment of his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","48072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599666","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-19","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-19T16:48:45.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599666/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599666/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-11","Department for International Trade: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, which agreed EU directives have not yet been transposed directly into UK law; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","48182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599668","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-17","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation.</p><p>There are no outstanding directives waiting to be transposed that fall under the jurisdiction of the Department for Exiting the European Union.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-17T14:50:19.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599668/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599668/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599668/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-11","Department for Exiting the European Union: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, which agreed EU directives have not yet been transposed directly into UK law; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","48177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599669","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-17","<p>While the UK remains a full member of the European Union it retains all of the rights, obligations and benefits that membership brings. The long-term relationship between the UK and the EIB will need to be resolved as part of the UK’s withdrawal from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer is the UK Governor of the European Investment Bank and continues to fulfil his governance duties. The Chancellor continues to meet his European counterparts on a regular basis to discuss a range of issues.</p><p> </p><p>The EIB publish all loans made to UK borrowers as well as details on all future projects yet to be financed. Between 2013 and 2015, the UK received €20.7bn in EIB financing. The link below provides full details on EIB lending to the UK.</p><p>http://www.eib.org/projects/regions/european-union/united-kingdom/index.htm</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","48058 ; 48059 ; 48063","2016-10-17T11:10:18.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599669/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599669/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-11","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which projects in the UK are (a) currently funded and (b) due to be funded by the European Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","48057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599670","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-17","<p>While the UK remains a full member of the European Union it retains all of the rights, obligations and benefits that membership brings. The long-term relationship between the UK and the EIB will need to be resolved as part of the UK’s withdrawal from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer is the UK Governor of the European Investment Bank and continues to fulfil his governance duties. The Chancellor continues to meet his European counterparts on a regular basis to discuss a range of issues.</p><p> </p><p>The EIB publish all loans made to UK borrowers as well as details on all future projects yet to be financed. Between 2013 and 2015, the UK received €20.7bn in EIB financing. The link below provides full details on EIB lending to the UK.</p><p>http://www.eib.org/projects/regions/european-union/united-kingdom/index.htm</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","48057 ; 48059 ; 48063","2016-10-17T11:10:19.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599670/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599670/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-11","European Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his plans are for the UK's future relationship with the European Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","48058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599671","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-17","<p>While the UK remains a full member of the European Union it retains all of the rights, obligations and benefits that membership brings. The long-term relationship between the UK and the EIB will need to be resolved as part of the UK’s withdrawal from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer is the UK Governor of the European Investment Bank and continues to fulfil his governance duties. The Chancellor continues to meet his European counterparts on a regular basis to discuss a range of issues.</p><p> </p><p>The EIB publish all loans made to UK borrowers as well as details on all future projects yet to be financed. Between 2013 and 2015, the UK received €20.7bn in EIB financing. The link below provides full details on EIB lending to the UK.</p><p>http://www.eib.org/projects/regions/european-union/united-kingdom/index.htm</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","48057 ; 48058 ; 48063","2016-10-17T11:10:19.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599671/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599671/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-11","European Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent meetings he has had with representatives of the European Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","48059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599673","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-17","<p>While the UK remains a full member of the European Union it retains all of the rights, obligations and benefits that membership brings. The long-term relationship between the UK and the EIB will need to be resolved as part of the UK’s withdrawal from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer is the UK Governor of the European Investment Bank and continues to fulfil his governance duties. The Chancellor continues to meet his European counterparts on a regular basis to discuss a range of issues.</p><p> </p><p>The EIB publish all loans made to UK borrowers as well as details on all future projects yet to be financed. Between 2013 and 2015, the UK received €20.7bn in EIB financing. The link below provides full details on EIB lending to the UK.</p><p>http://www.eib.org/projects/regions/european-union/united-kingdom/index.htm</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","48057 ; 48058 ; 48059","2016-10-17T11:10:18.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599673/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599673/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-11","European Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much the UK received in funding from the European Investment Bank in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","48063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599674","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Department does not track the costs of individual meetings. Details about overseas visits and related expenditure for Ministers and Senior Officials will be published as transparency data on gov.uk.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-17T15:44:21.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599674/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599674/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-11","Department for Exiting the European Union: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 10 October 2016 to Question 46424, if he will estimate the total cost of meetings held by his Department to date; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","48126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599675","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-17","<p>The Prime Minister has committed to full engagement with the Devolved Administrations to get the best possible deal for all parts of our United Kingdom as we leave the EU.The Secretary of State for Exiting the EU has spoken with First Minister Nicola Sturgeon about developing a UK approach for EU exit. He has also met with Michael Russell, the Scottish Government Minister for UK Negotiations on Scotland’s Place in Europe, to discuss the work of the Department for Exiting the EU.We will give the Devolved Administrations every opportunity to have their say as we form our negotiating strategy and we will look at any suggestions they put forward.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-17T16:04:21.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599675/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599675/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-11","Brexit: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many meetings the Government has had with Ministers of the Scottish Government on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","48004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599676","Department of Health","false","2016-10-19","<p>The future arrangements which apply in relation to European Union institutions based in the United Kingdom should be determined once the UK has left the EU. It is too early to speculate on the future location of the European Medicines Agency.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-10-19T14:44:15.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599676/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599676/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-11","European Medicines Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what preparations his Department has made for the likely relocation of the headquarters of the European Medicines Agency away from London after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","47934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599678","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-17","<p>Defra is assessing impacts on the meat sector from EU Exit and is committed to ensuring continued access to vital markets in Europe on the basis of the UK’s high standards of welfare and animal health. In addition, good progress is being made in extending access to international markets such as China, USA and Japan.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-10-17T17:01:43.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599678/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599678/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-11","Meat: UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the export of meat from the UK to other EU member states.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","48206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599679","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-17","<p>A World Trade Organisation member can enter into a preferential trade deal, such as a Free Trade Agreement, with another member.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-10-17T13:29:49.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599679/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599679/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-11","UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether his Department has made an assessment of whether tariff free trade between the UK and EU member states would be possible under World Trade Organisation rules.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","48207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603863","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>The National Living Wage has already given one million people a pay rise, helping build an economy that works for all. The Government will continue to consider expert advice on future increases in the National Living Wage from the Low Pay Commission.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-10-17T16:03:18.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603863/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603863/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Living Wage: Unemployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the national living wage on unemployment levels.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","906599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603864","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>This Government and my Department recognise that supporting ex-offenders into work is a crucial part of effective rehabilitation. I am in regular contact with the Minister for Prisons, and we will be meeting on this issue next week.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-10-17T15:43:36.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603864/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603864/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Employment: Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Justice on increasing the employment rate of ex-offenders.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","906600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603865","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>We have a well-established regime of checks and balances in place, for example the Pension Protection Fund and the Pensions Regulator. The Government keeps this framework for pensions under constant review, and amends it when evidence demonstrates such change is needed</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-10-17T15:52:10.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603865/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603865/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps the Government is taking to help protect the pensions of long-serving employees.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","906582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603866","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-17","<p>Since 2010 the youth claimant count has fallen in all regions, and only 5.7% of the youth population are unemployed and not in full-time education, a rate that is near record low. We are investing further in an intensive support regime for young people, equipping them with vital skills to not only find a job, but build capability to sustain work.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-10-17T15:26:04.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603866/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603866/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-11","Unemployment: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to reduce youth unemployment in areas with high levels of youth unemployment.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","906596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605548","Wales Office","false","2016-10-19","<p>The Prime Minister has committed to full engagement with the Devolved Administrations to get the best possible deal for all parts of our United Kingdom as we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>We will give the Welsh Government every opportunity to have their say as we form our negotiating strategy and we will look at any suggestions they put forward.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-10-19T14:17:59.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605548/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605548/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605548/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-10-11","Brexit: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what discussions he has had with the Welsh Government on its role in negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","906622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605549","Wales Office","false","2016-10-19","<p>The Government is taking a practical approach to EU funding. As my Rt hon Friend the Chancellor has made clear, structural and investment funds projects signed before the date of exit will be fully funded by the Treasury even where payments fall after we leave the EU; in keeping with the devolution settlement, it will be for the Welsh Government to decide the conditions used to assess projects within its devolved competence.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-10-19T14:13:33.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605549/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605549/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605549/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-10-11","EU Grants and Loans: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what steps he is taking to ensure that Wales receives the maximum funding possible from the EU before the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","906620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598055","Home Office","false","2016-10-24","<p>Current trade between the UK and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) is minimal and covered by an overarching provision that any activities should satisfy existing UN and EU sanctions. These refer to restriction in the export of goods and financial assistance, which may contribute to the development of the DPRK's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.</p><p>The Modern Slavery Act 2015 introduced a landmark transparency in supply chains provision. This requires all commercial organisations operating in the UK with a turnover of £36m or more to set out what steps they have taken to prevent modern slavery in their business and supply chains each year. This mandatory reporting will allow consumers, investors, campaigners and others to scrutinise the activities of businesses and call businesses to account if they are not doing enough, including in relation to North Korean nationals.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-10-24T13:29:08.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598055/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598055/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-10","Forced Labour: North Korea","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that UK-owned companies do not facilitate the forced labour of North Korean nationals.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598056","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-19","<p>We are aware of reports of thirty North Koreans being sent back to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) after a period of detention in China.</p><p>Despite claims by the DPRK authorities that forcibly repatriated refugees are well treated and reintegrated into DPRK society, reports suggest that they are often mistreated by the authorities.</p><p>We will raise the issue of non-refoulement at the next UK-China Human rights Dialogue, scheduled to take place this month.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL2195","2016-10-19T15:21:45.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598056/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598056/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-10","North Korea: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of reports that the government of China has recently breached the United Nations Refugee Convention by refouling 30 North Koreans without giving them an opportunity to claim asylum nor to meet representatives of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598057","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-24","<p>As part of UN and EU sanctions, banks are required to close existing branches, subsidiaries or accounts in North Korea where it has been determined that they contribute to North Korea’s ballistic missile programmes. The sanctions also prohibit any commercial activity by the Government of North Korea (including legal persons, entities or bodies owned or controlled by them).</p><p>Assets owned or controlled in the EU by designated DPRK persons, entities or bodies, including government bodies, are subject to an asset freeze and cannot be traded on the London Stock Exchange. A list of designations which has been placed in the Library includes a number of DPRK government and state-owned bodies. HM Treasury implements these financial sanctions in the UK. Non-compliance with financial sanctions is a criminal offence and HM Treasury works closely with law enforcement to ensure sanctions breaches are dealt with appropriately. For reasons of confidentiality, the Treasury does not make public the details of individual reports of frozen assets.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-10-24T13:49:21.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598057/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598057/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-10","Financial Services: North Korea","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the government of North Korea, or any of its state-owned companies, has access to the London Stock Exchange or holds financial interests in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598058","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Government does not have data on the number of companies owned by UK nationals or headquartered in the UK which conduct business with the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).</p><p>Data on the value of trade between the UK and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea is published by HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC). In 2015 the total bilateral trade in goods between the UK and the DPRK was $814,700.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-10-24T14:47:07.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598058/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598058/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-10","Overseas Trade: North Korea","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the number of companies owned by UK nationals or headquartered in the UK which conduct business with the government of North Korea or any of its state-owned companies.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598059","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-20","<p>The Government has made no such assessment.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-10-20T11:10:57.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598059/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598059/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-10","North Korea: Sanctions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the effect of the United States' North Korea Sanctions and Policy Enhancement Act of 2016 (H.R. 757) on UK-owned businesses and UK nationals which conduct business with the government of North Korea or its state-owned companies.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598060","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-19","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) projects in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) are usually delivered through international Non-Governmental Organisations who operate in-country and are aimed at assisting some of the most vulnerable groups in North Korean society. Before selecting an implementing partner relevant due diligence checks are carried out which include, but are not limited to, obtaining assurances about: training provided to staff in relation to reporting bribery and corruption; how those concerns are shared with donors; and what policies, principles and procedures the organisation has in place to regulate its own conduct.</p><p>In line with standard FCO project requirements detailed budgets are required for all projects and these are carefully checked to ensure both in-country and other costs are reasonable. Project implementers are required to provide financial reports and originals or copies of all invoices and receipts, as well as a Project Completion Report containing a detailed breakdown of all expenditure during the project period. The final payment on any project is only released after submission of a satisfactory Project Completion Report.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-19T15:22:53.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598060/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598060/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-10","North Korea: Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they ensure that funds spent by the British Embassy in Pyongyang or funds dispersed by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office for North Korea activities are not diverted by the government of North Korea for use in its nuclear programme or human rights abuses.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598061","Home Office","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 applies to houses or flats where the premises are not occupied as a private dwelling, including properties offering short term accommodation to paying guests.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-10-24T13:16:09.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598061/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598061/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-10","Holiday Accommodation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to ensure that commercial short-term lettings of accommodation, such as those offered by the AirBnB website, are safe and comply with fire regulations.","false","Biography information for Baroness Bakewell of Hardington Mandeville",,"Baroness Bakewell of Hardington Mandeville","HL2090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598062","Home Office","false","2016-10-24","<p>There is no current intention to disaggregate hate crime data on the grounds of race, but we will keep that under review. Since 2010, we have improved police recording of hate crime. Forces now capture data on all five of the monitored hate crime strands, and from April this year, forces have started to disaggregate hate crime data on the grounds of religion.</p><p>We have noted the findings of the Council of Europe’s European Commission on Racism and Intolerance following an inspection of the United Kingdom earlier this year. The Government’s full response to the report can be found as an annex to the publication.</p><p>We are clear that there is no excuse for hate crime against anyone of any nationality, ethnicity or religious background - it has no place whatsoever in our diverse society. This commitment is underpinned by some of the strongest legislation in the world.</p><p>We welcome that the Commission has recognised the strength of our new hate crime action plan which will help reduce hate crime, increase reporting and improve support for victims. The hate crime action plan contains specific measures to increase the rate of prosecution and ensure that enhanced sentencing powers are used where appropriate.</p><p>These measures include refreshed Crown Prosecution Service policy and legal guidance for prosecutors on racially and religiously aggravated crime and on prosecuting social media cases, and publicising convictions and information on enhanced sentencing outcomes.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-10-24T13:30:53.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598062/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598062/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-10","Hate Crime","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will implement the recommendation made by the Committee on Elimination of Racial Discrimination to collect systemically disaggregated data on hate crimes.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598063","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-24","<p>The National Minimum Wage naming and shaming scheme represents the end point of civil sanctions against employers who fail to pay at least the appropriate rate of minimum wage to their workers. Where there is evidence that an offence has been committed the case will always be considered for criminal investigation which may in turn result in prosecutions. But criminal investigations are reserved for the most serious cases of non-compliance.</p><p> </p><p>Our number one priority is getting workers the money they are owed and the civil route is more successful in achieving this. Criminal investigations by HM Revenue &amp; Customs and prosecutions by the Crown Prosecution Service will not necessarily result in arrears of wages being paid back to the workers. This would require further civil prosecutions following the Courts’ ruling.</p><p> </p><p>Under the civil route, employers are not only faced with reputational consequences, but also face a financial penalty for breaking the law.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-24T16:00:16.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598063/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598063/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-10","Minimum Wage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, of the 700 employers "named and shamed" by them since October 2013 for failing to pay the minimum wage, how many were prosecuted; of those, how many prosecutions were successful; and what steps they plan to take to increase the number of prosecutions.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598064","Department of Health","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Department has commissioned the Law Commission to carry out a review of the Deprivation of Liberty Safeguards. The review is expected to be published at the end of the year.</p><p> </p><p>The Department will consider what steps may be necessary to improve the system in light of the review.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-10-24T12:25:26.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598064/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598064/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-10","Mental Capacity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the number of Deprivation of Liberty orders sought by care home owners and the proportion which are rejected, whether they are considering taking steps to improve the system; and if so, when they will publish details of those planned steps.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598065","Home Office","false","2016-10-24","<p>Since 2010, we have improved police recording of hate crime. Forces now capture data on all five of the monitored hate crime strands, and from April this year, forces have started to disaggregate hate crime data on the grounds of religion.</p><p>We have noted the findings of the Council of Europe’s European Commission on Racism and Intolerance following an inspection of the United Kingdom earlier this year. The Government’s full response to the report can be found as an annex to the publication.</p><p>We are clear that there is no excuse for hate crime against anyone of any nationality, ethnicity or religious background - it has no place whatsoever in our diverse society. This commitment is underpinned by some of the strongest legislation in the world.</p><p>We welcome that the Commission has recognised the strength of our new hate crime action plan which will help reduce hate crime, increase reporting and improve support for victims. The hate crime action plan contains specific measures to increase the rate of prosecution and ensure that enhanced sentencing powers are used where appropriate.</p><p>These measures include refreshed Crown Prosecution Service policy and legal guidance for prosecutors on racially and religiously aggravated crime and on prosecuting social media cases, and publicising convictions and information on enhanced sentencing outcomes.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-10-24T13:20:19.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598065/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598065/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-10","Hate Crime","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their response to the report by the Council of Europe about the incidence of hate crime in the UK, the apparent failure to prosecute such crimes, and the lack of data on the use of extended sentencing powers.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598066","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-24","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply. What happens in terms of the migration system that will be established as we leave the EU is a matter that will be very closely scrutinised and looked at in great detail by the government and within the government.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-10-24T12:30:09.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598066/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598066/answer","Lord Beecham (HL2095) v4docx (2).pdf ; Table For HL2095 (2).xls","Lord Beecham (HL2095) v4docx (2).pdf ; Table For HL2095 (2).xls","UKSA response to HL2095 ; UKSA table response to HL2095","UKSA response to HL2095 ; UKSA table response to HL2095","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598066/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-10","Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many (1) EU students, and (2) students of other nationalities, remain in the UK after completing their university courses in the UK; and in each case for how long on average.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598067","Home Office","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Home Office and Department of Health have been working to increase the use of alternative joint health and policing approaches and interventions that reduce the need for the police to use their formal powers of detention under section 136 of the Mental Health Act. Whilst overall police use of section 136 has increased, from just under 15,000 in 2011/12 to 19,410 in 2014/15, the use of police cells has reduced from just under 9,000 in 2011/12 to 2,100 in 2015/16.</p><p>As a result of joint work with the Department of Health those suffering a mental health crisis are more likely to be offered alternative support. The introduction of initiatives such as street triage schemes and community based places of safety provide an alternative to the use of police cells. These types of interventions are proving successful and the Home Office is seeking to promote their use nationally using the £15m funding made available by the Department of Health to increase the availability of alternative places of safety.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-10-24T13:28:03.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598067/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598067/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-10","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions have taken place between the Home Office and the Department of Health in relation to the increase in the use by the police of powers of detention under section 136 of the Mental Health Act; and with what result.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598068","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-18","<p>My Rt hon. Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade’s CV is available on gov.uk.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-10-18T11:47:11.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598068/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598068/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-10","Liam Fox","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what experience the Secretary of State for International Trade has had of working inside British business.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL2097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598069","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-24","<p>The UK is one of the most dynamic and competitive economies in the world, as borne out by measures of the effectiveness of UK competition policy and regulation, for example:</p><p> </p><p>•The UK is ranked 2<sup>nd</sup> in the OECD for the pro-competition stance of its regulatory policies</p><p> </p><p>•The World Economic Forum rated the UK 3<sup>rd</sup> (out of 138) for the intensity of local competition, 12<sup>th</sup> for the extent of market dominance, and 10<sup>th</sup> for the effectiveness of our anti-monopoly policies.</p><p> </p><p>As a result, we are ranked 6th out of 189 countries in the World Bank Doing Business Index; and 7th out of 138 countries (improving our ranking from 10th last year) in the World Economic Forum Global Competitiveness Index.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-24T12:36:45.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598069/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598069/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-10","Business","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the dynamism and capability of the UK business sector.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL2098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598070","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-24","<p>The EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which will come into force in all EU Member States on 25 May 2018, establishes a tiered approach to penalties for breaches which enables Data Protection Authorities to impose fines for the most serious infringements of up to the higher of 4% of annual worldwide turnover or EUR20 million. Other specified infringements would attract a fine of up to the higher of 2% of annual worldwide turnover or EUR10m.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-10-24T14:19:12.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598070/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598070/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-10","Information Commissioner","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are planning to raise the level of the maximum fine that can be imposed by the Information Commissioner.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL2099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598071","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-24","<p>I have been asked to reply on behalf of the Home Office.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will shortly be consulting on proposals to tighten the Resident Labour Market Test, which businesses have to undertake before sponsoring individuals under Tier 2 (General), the skilled work route for non-EEA nationals.</p><p> </p><p>This is not about listing foreign workers or so-called “naming and shaming” of companies. This information will not be published. The proportion of international workers in a company is one of the pieces of information that we might decide to take into account, as part of our work to ensure that companies take reasonable steps to recruit at home before looking to bring in workers from abroad.</p><p> </p><p>We will listen to businesses throughout the consultation and use that feedback to inform our decisions.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-24T15:52:45.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598071/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598071/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-10","Companies: Migrant Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what obligations they intend to place on companies to list their foreign workers.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL2100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598072","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-25","<p>The Government is consulting widely through meetings all over the country with academics, think tanks, businesses, charities, universities and more to ensure that all views can be reflected in our analysis of the options for the UK’s withdrawal from the European Union.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-10-25T14:44:16.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598072/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598072/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-10","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are planning to publish a consultation paper setting out and assessing the different routes to Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL2101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598073","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-18","<p>The UK has an inflation target, not an exchange rate target, and Her Majesty’s Government does not express a view on the level of exchange rates. Instead, the exchange rate is allowed to adjust flexibly in response to economic conditions and movements in sterling are determined by market forces.</p><p> </p><p>This framework means we do not need to introduce exchange rate controls.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham","HL2120","2016-10-18T14:25:15.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598073/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598073/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-10","Sterling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether the drop in the value of sterling in recent months reflects the markets' view of the likely future health of the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL2102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598074","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-18","<p>We welcome the Sense report, Realising Aspirations for All and its findings. We want all disabled and people with a long term health condition to fulfil their potential and achieve their aspirations.</p><p>We will soon publish a Green Paper on work and health and conduct a consultation to understand how every individual can have the opportunity to work and share in the economic and health benefits that work brings, regardless of their health condition or disability. We will continue to engage with Sense and other key stakeholders as part of the Green Paper consultation.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-10-18T16:33:32.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598074/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598074/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-10","Disability: Employment Schemes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the recommendation in the recent report from the charity Sense, <i>Realising Aspirations for All</i>, to break the link between welfare benefits and access to employment by making support voluntary and available to all disabled people, regardless of the benefits they claim.","false","Biography information for Baroness Eaton",,"Baroness Eaton","HL2103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598075","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Government recognises that people need support that is tailored to their needs. Personal Budgets are currently being trialled in Access to Work to offer customers greater flexibility to manage their Travel to Work or Support Worker costs. Initial findings from the trial are expected in early 2017.</p><p>The Work and Health Unit, in partnership with NHS England, are also exploring options for trialling the expansion of personal health budgets to include employment support through the work and health Innovation Fund. This is being considered as part of a small number of health-led employment support trials that we hope to set up with devolution areas and as part of the ongoing development of Integrated Personal Commissioning where employment could be considered as part of a wider conversation to support the roll out of personal health budgets.</p><p>A Personal Budgets model was previously tested in the Right to Control Trailblazers, which ran from 2010 to 2013. Disabled people taking part in the trailblazers were offered greater choice and control over the support they received, as well as the option to take a direct payment and arrange their own support. The final evaluation report did not find any evidence that the Right to Control Trailblazers had a significant positive impact on customers, both overall and by subgroup.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-10-24T12:42:10.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598075/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598075/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-10","Disability: Employment Schemes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to trialling the introduction of personal budgets for employment support in order to support more disabled people into work.","false","Biography information for Baroness Eaton",,"Baroness Eaton","HL2104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598076","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-18","<p>The Rt Hon Lord Bates has been appointed as Minister of State at the Department for International Development (DfID).</p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park",,"2016-10-18T15:57:10.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598076/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598076/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-10","Department for International Development: Ministers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to appoint a new Minister of State for the Department for International Development in the House of Lords as a replacement for the current Minister; and if so, when they intend to make that appointment.","false","Biography information for Lord Foulkes of Cumnock",,"Lord Foulkes of Cumnock","HL2105"
